Perspectives for Sino-American Relations 2019
NEW YORK – In 2018, the new and increasingly unpredictable dynamics of China-US relations unsettled much of Asia.
Exactly a year ago, US President Donald Trump returned from his particularly pompous "State Visit Plus" in Beijing, which China had hoped would finally put an end to Trump's anti-Chinese campaign rhetoric.
Twelve months later, China and the United States are embroiled in a trade war, and the Trump administration has replaced the "strategic engagement" of the US in China with "strategic competition".
Additionally, the US, European, and Chinese economies and markets were booming a year ago.
Today, there is great uncertainty on the financial markets, with growth slowing down in China and Europe, and higher interest rates beginning to take effect in America.
The uncertainty over the future development of nuclear talks with North Korea also contributes to this picture.
So, what are the prospects for Sino-American relations in 2019?
It is likely that there will be an agreement by March on reducing the bilateral trade deficit and on the import decisions that China will make in this regard.
An agreement on tariff reductions is also possible by then, although the complexity of the issue could extend the timeline.
If one tariff after another were to be negotiated, a year could pass.
However, if Chinese economic reformers were to choose a more drastic approach by gradually committing to abolishing all tariffs over time and urging Americans to do the same, a faster result might be obtained.
This would, however, go against the instincts of Chinese trade officials who have been trained for decades to be frugal and reluctant to give up anything, let alone everything at once.
Reforming so-called forced technology transfer should be relatively straightforward.
Nevertheless, reform is something other than the way contractual agreements are implemented in practice, even if there are no specific provisions for technology transfer.
Intellectual property protection, however, is extremely problematic.
Previous agreements made during the government of President Barack Obama could be reaffirmed.
However, the enforcement or judicial proceedings for violations of intellectual property rights remain a hopeless endeavor.
A possible mechanism is to submit relevant contracts between Chinese and foreign companies to international trade arbitration tribunals based in Singapore or Switzerland, which are specifically tasked with enforcing intellectual property protection.
If China were to object, it could develop its own international trade arbitration procedure based in China.
For this, it would need to appoint qualified foreigners to its arbitration panel to strengthen international credibility.
No one has trust in Chinese trade courts.
For its own domestic reform needs, China must move towards completely independent trade and civil courts within its judicial system, even if the criminal court remains under political control.
The American concerns regarding state subsidies under China's "Made in China 2025" strategy will hardly be alleviated.
In fact, all countries provide some level of state support to their domestic technology sectors, with China having the highest level.
Even if we were to prescribe a maximum level of state support for a particular company, it would be difficult to enforce.
I am not optimistic that we will reach a negotiated agreement in this area.
Perhaps America should simply outcompete China by increasing public investments in research and development in the fields of information technology and biotechnology.
We should also not rule out the possibility that China might offer tariff reforms to the rest of the international community.
In time, China could decide to take the drastic step of agreeing to tariff-free trade not only with the US, but with all member states of the World Trade Organization.
China would thus be offered a nearly irresistible opportunity to position itself as a champion of global free trade and counter the trend of protectionism.
As part of such a shift, China could invite TPP member states to join, in order to surpass the US (which has withdrawn from the free trade agreement as one of its first acts under Trump) in the Asia-Pacific region.
China can be remarkably agile when it discovers a political opening and market access.
The negotiations would be difficult, but Japan's reservations about China's accession to the TPP have decreased since Prime Minister Shinzo Abe's recent visit to Beijing.
Given the central strategic challenges in its relationship with the US, China is likely to be focused in 2019 on reducing conflicts in its relations with other countries in general foreign and security policy.
In relations with Japan, there is already a certain normalization.
Recent data from the Japanese Coast Guard indicate a significant reduction in Chinese incursions into the area of the Senkaku/Diaoyu Islands in the East China Sea.
China is also trying to reduce tensions with the Association of Southeast Asian Nations over the South China Sea by accelerating the negotiation of a "code of conduct".
Furthermore, China is likely to have a more relaxed relationship with India after the bilateral summit in Wuhan in April.
And China might begin to moderate its stance towards Taiwan, given the electoral setback suffered by the Democratic Progressive Party of Taiwanese President Tsai Ing-wen, who supports independence, in the local and regional elections last month.
This would naturally change radically if the US were to continue significant arms sales to Taiwan, which is likely.
Incidents at sea with the US in the South China Sea will continue, and the conflict could escalate if the US were to assert its stance on "freedom of navigation" more forcefully next year.
China will continue to implement its major project, the "New Silk Road", across all of Eurasia.
However, the initiative has caused less political uproar in China in recent months.
There are already discussions among Chinese officials about revising certain aspects of the project, following Sri Lanka's handover of the Hambantota port to China, which triggered negative reactions and concerns about the long-term financial viability of the New Silk Road.
2019 might hear less frequent triumphant announcements about the New Silk Road.
Furthermore, China is likely to strengthen and expand its role within the United Nations and existing Bretton Woods institutions, rather than emphasizing new institutions of international political action.
It will likely continue to appear as a new advocate of the WHO and maintain its stance on global climate change, as agreed upon in the Paris Climate Agreement of 2015.
More seasoned representatives of China's foreign policy establishment believe it is better to focus on existing mechanisms of the global rule-based system, especially if the US consistently shows contempt for it.
While China attempts to stabilize its relations with the US and reduce tensions in its relations with other countries, its leadership will likely use 2019 to form a well-informed opinion about the future of US policy: the consequences of the Mueller investigation for Trump and his government, and whether a new president in 2020 (or earlier) would change the new US strategy in any way.
Although they have already concluded that the US stance towards China has undergone a profound change, they are still uncertain about the exact form this change takes and whether a fundamental shift in strategy (as opposed to tactical measures) is indicated.
